body:
Given an envoy running with a config.json such as:
```
{
   "admin" : {
      "access_log_path" : "/dev/null",
      "address" : "tcp://127.0.0.1:9901"
   },
   "cluster_manager" : {
      "clusters" : [
         {
            "hosts" : [
               {
                  "url" : "tcp://127.0.0.1:8080"
               }
            ],
            "name" : "0-service-cluster",
            "lb_type" : "round_robin",
            "type" : "static",
            "connect_timeout_ms" : 250
         }
      ]
   },
   "listeners" : [
      {
         "address" : "tcp://0.0.0.0:61001",
         "ssl_context" : {
            "cert_chain_file" : "/cert.pem",
            "private_key_file" : "/key.pem"
         },
         "filters" : [
            {
               "type" : "read",
               "name" : "tcp_proxy",
               "config" : {
                  "stat_prefix" : "ingress_tcp",
                  "route_config" : {
                     "routes" : [
                        {
                           "cluster" : "0-service-cluster"
                        }
                     ]
                  }
               }
            }
         ]
      }
   ]
}
```

and a upstream server such as:
```
while true; do { echo -e "HTTP/1.1 200 OK\r\n\r\n"; echo "hello, envoy"; } | nc -l 8080; done
```
a curl request to `curl -vvvk https://localhost:61001` will hang forever, generating envoy debug logs as follows:

```                                                  
[2017-10-24 00:00:23.894][2831][info][main] source/server/connection_handler_impl.cc:129] [C9] new connection                                   
[2017-10-24 00:00:23.895][2831][info][filter] source/common/filter/tcp_proxy.cc:117] [C9] new tcp proxy session                                 
[2017-10-24 00:00:23.895][2831][debug][filter] source/common/filter/tcp_proxy.cc:191] [C9] Creating connection to cluster 0-service-cluster     
[2017-10-24 00:00:23.895][2831][debug][connection] source/common/network/connection_impl.cc:523] [C10] connecting to 127.0.0.1:8080             
[2017-10-24 00:00:23.895][2831][debug][connection] source/common/network/connection_impl.cc:532] [C10] connection in progress                   
[2017-10-24 00:00:23.895][2831][debug][connection] source/common/ssl/connection_impl.cc:127] [C9] handshake error: 2                            
[2017-10-24 00:00:23.895][2831][debug][connection] source/common/network/connection_impl.cc:492] [C10] connected                                
[2017-10-24 00:00:23.895][2831][debug][connection] source/common/ssl/connection_impl.cc:127] [C9] handshake error: 2                            
[2017-10-24 00:00:23.895][2831][debug][connection] source/common/network/connection_impl.cc:447] [C10] remote close                             
[2017-10-24 00:00:23.895][2831][debug][connection] source/common/network/connection_impl.cc:159] [C10] closing socket: 0                        
[2017-10-24 00:00:23.895][2831][debug][connection] source/common/network/connection_impl.cc:126] [C9] closing data_to_write=33 type=0           
[2017-10-24 00:00:23.895][2831][debug][connection] source/common/ssl/connection_impl.cc:127] [C9] handshake error: 2                            
```

after CTRL-C'ing the curl request, envoy logs:
```                                                       
[2017-10-24 00:00:28.362][2831][debug][connection] source/common/network/connection_impl.cc:383] [C9] remote early close                        
[2017-10-24 00:00:28.362][2831][debug][connection] source/common/network/connection_impl.cc:159] [C9] closing socket: 0                         
[2017-10-24 00:00:28.362][2831][info][main] source/server/connection_handler_impl.cc:59] [C9] adding to cleanup list
```

I expect the curl request to complete and return `hello, envoy`.

I can make the curl request succeed by adding `-q 1` to the netcat command, which makes netcat wait a second before closing the socket. This indicates that the problem is around the fact that `nc` will immediately close the connection after sending its data. The envoy logs that indicate a `remote close` and subsequent handshake error also help to validate that theory. This will also work if I remove the `ssl_context` directive.

This was reproducible using the latest docker image of `lyft/envoy`.
